# [6MAN](../wg/6man.html)

## Summary

The 6MAN Working Group met at IETF 126 to discuss the status of active working group documents, coordinate protocol work with other working groups, and review several active and individual proposals. Key topics included Wi-Fi multicast optimization, sub-link scoped multicast addressing, updating IPv6 Node Requirements, expanding the IPv6 loopback address prefix, flow label load-balancing for RoCEv2, and ICMP error handling in SRv6 VPNs.

---

## Key Discussion Points

### Working Group Administration & Document Status
*Presented by Jen Linkova*
* Slide Deck: [00_Chairs_Slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-6man-00-chairs-slides-00)

* **Document Progress**: 
  * "Cluster 525" has been unblocked by changing the SNAC Simple reference from normative to informative.
  * `draft-ietf-6man-ipv6-neighbor-discovery-yang` is waiting for write-up clarifications.
  * `draft-ietf-6man-slaac-renum` is currently in Working Group Last Call (WGLC). Zafar Ali noted that while significant comments are being addressed, convergence is slow due to concerns regarding hardware implementation complexity, inconsistency in encoding, and privacy risks associated with a 32-bit ID (such as hijacking for application IDs).
* **Dormant/Expired Drafts Cleanup**: The chairs proposed moving dormant or expired working group documents (such as the RFC 4291 bis document) back to individual status if no objections are received before September 1.
  * Tim Chown asked about the history of RFC 4291 bis. Bob Hinden clarified that it was blocked at the IESG due to a lack of consensus on prefix representation.
  * Jordi Palet Martinez suggested sending separate emails to the mailing list for each affected draft to allow for informed feedback.
  * Ron Bonica asked if the "reflection draft" (waiting in the RFC Editor queue for a missing reference to RFC 8335 bis) could be unblocked by referencing the original RFC 8335 instead. Eric Vyncke (AD) preferred to keep the bis reference and apply pressure to the INTAREA working group to advance the bis document.
* **Coordination with Other WGs**: Jen Linkova reiterated that if a proposal in another working group requires changes to the IPv6 protocol (e.g., new options or bits), that working group must first adopt the draft and agree on the problem statement and solution before 6MAN acts on the protocol specifications. Ted Lemon, Joel Halpern (SAVNET co-chair), and Eric Vyncke agreed with this approach to prevent premature discussions in 6MAN.

