### IPv6 Wants 802.11 Flexible Multicast Service
*Presented by David Lamparter*
* Draft: [draft-ietf-6man-ieee80211-fms](../id/draft-ietf-6man-ieee80211-fms.html)
* Slide Deck: [IPv6 wants 802.11 Flexible Multicast Service](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-6man-ipv6-wants-80211-flexible-multicast-service-00)

* **Discussion**:
  * David Lamparter presented the issue of multicast packet loss on Wi-Fi, which frequently breaks IPv6 Router Advertisements (RAs). Due to power-saving mechanisms, Wi-Fi chipsets often sleep through multicast transmissions unless the DTIM multiplier is high. 
  * Two Layer 2 features exist to mitigate this: Flexible Multicast Service (FMS) and Directed Multicast Service (DMS). Neither is currently implemented in `hostapd`. The goal of this draft is to serve as a liaison to the Wi-Fi Alliance and IEEE 802.11 to encourage implementation.
  * Jerome Henry noted that FMS (standardized in 2008) has high overhead when multiple stations negotiate different intervals. He stated that DMS is already part of the Wi-Fi Alliance power-save certification and suggested gathering real-world data to present directly to the Wi-Fi Alliance.
  * Lorenzo Colitti agreed DMS is a better candidate but questioned whether it allows for enough buffering to save battery.
  * Suresh Krishnan remarked that getting changes into `hostapd` is notoriously difficult from the outside, which stalls deployment on cheaper APs.
  * Eric Vyncke committed to adding the draft to the official IEEE-IETF liaison tracking list.

