### ICMP Error Handling for VPNs in SRv6 Networks
*Joint Discussion of draft-varhal-6man-icmp-srv6-vpn & draft-ali-6man-srv6-vpn-icmp-error-handling*
* Slide Decks:
  * [06_ICMP Error Handling for VPNs in SRv6 Networks: draft-varhal-6man-icmp-srv6-vpn](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-6man-icmp-error-handling-for-vpns-in-srv6-networks-draft-varhal-6man-icmp-srv6-vpn-00) (Presented by Balazs Varga)
  * [07_draft-ali-6man-srv6-vpn-icmp-error-handling-04](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-6man-draft-ali-6man-srv6-vpn-icmp-error-handling-04-00) (Presented by Zafar Ali)

* **Discussion**:
  * Balazs Varga presented `draft-varhal-6man-icmp-srv6-vpn`, focusing on using ping/traceroute to locate failures in SRv6 networks. It proposes modifying the source IP address at the ingress PE to be VPN-specific so that ICMP errors can be mapped back to the correct customer VPN.
  * Zafar Ali presented `draft-ali-6man-srv6-vpn-icmp-error-handling`, focusing on returning transit ICMP errors (like Packet Too Big) to customer CEs. It replicates MPLS behavior by having the P-node copy the destination VPN SID from the invoking packet into the outer destination address of the ICMP error, allowing the egress PE to forward it back to the customer.
  * Jen Linkova questioned a slide in Zafar's deck showing source IP spoofing (using the PE1 address instead of the local P1 address). Zafar agreed it should be the local P-node address (P1) and will correct it.
  * Ron Bonica argued that the problem is common to all IP-in-IP tunnels (GRE, UDP, etc.) and suggested writing a generic solution instead of an SRv6-specific one. Zafar responded that operators prefer SRv6-specific implementation details.
  * Suresh Krishnan raised concerns that Zafar's approach requires P-nodes to be SRv6-aware. Zafar clarified that if P-nodes are not SRv6-aware, the fallback behavior routes packets back to the ingress PE (combining both drafts' approaches).
  * **Path Forward**: Eric Vyncke and Joel Halpern (SPRING co-chair) noted that because these drafts primarily govern SRv6 VPN architecture and operator philosophy, the SPRING working group should review the merged drafts first. Once SPRING agrees on the architecture, any necessary protocol or behavioral changes can be formally progressed in 6MAN or INTAREA.

